# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: translation-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The relative positions of structures along strands of nucleic acid, including genes and various protein binding sites, are usually noted as being either *upstream* (towards the 5′-end) or *downstream* (towards the 3′-end).
[src:translation-biology/3-end] Directionality is related to, but different from, sense.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] Transcription of single-stranded RNA from a double-stranded DNA template requires the selection of one strand of the DNA template as the template strand that directly interacts with the nascent RNA due to complementary sequence.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The other strand is not copied directly, but necessarily its sequence will be similar to that of the RNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] Transcription initiation sites generally occur on both strands of an organism's DNA, and specify the location, direction, and circumstances under which transcription will occur.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] If the transcript encodes one or (rarely) more proteins, translation of each protein by the ribosome will proceed in a 5′-to-3′ direction, and will extend the protein from its N-terminus toward its C-terminus.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] For example, in a typical gene a start codon (5′-ATG-3′) is a DNA sequence within the sense strand.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] Transcription begins at an upstream site (relative to the sense strand), and as it proceeds through the region it copies the 3′-TAC-5′ from the template strand to produce 5′-AUG-3′ within a messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The mRNA is scanned by the ribosome from the 5′ end, where the start codon directs the incorporation of a methionine (bacteria, mitochondria, and plastids use *N*-formylmethionine instead) at the N terminus of the protein.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] By convention, single strands of DNA and RNA sequences are written in a 5′-to-3′ direction except as needed to illustrate the pattern of base pairing.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 5′-end (pronounced "five prime end") designates the end of the DNA or RNA strand that has the fifth carbon in the sugar-ring of the deoxyribose or ribose at its terminus.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] A phosphate group attached to the 5′-end permits ligation of two nucleotides, i.e., the covalent binding of a 5′-phosphate to the 3′-hydroxyl group of another nucleotide, to form a phosphodiester bond.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] Removal of the 5′-phosphate prevents ligation.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] To prevent unwanted nucleic acid ligation (e.g. self-ligation of a plasmid vector in DNA cloning), molecular biologists commonly remove the 5′-phosphate with a phosphatase.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 5′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site at which post-transcriptional capping occurs, a process which is vital to producing mature messenger RNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] Capping increases the stability of the messenger RNA while it undergoes translation, providing resistance to the degradative effects of exonucleases.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] It consists of a methylated nucleotide (methylguanosine) attached to the messenger RNA in a rare 5′- to 5′-triphosphate linkage.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 5′-*flanking* region of a gene often denotes a region of DNA which is not transcribed into RNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 5′-flanking region contains the gene promoter, and may also contain enhancers or other protein binding sites.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 5′-*untranslated* region (5′-UTR) is a region of a gene which is transcribed into mRNA, and is located at the 5′-end of the mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] This region of an mRNA may or may not be translated, but is usually involved in the regulation of translation.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 5′-untranslated region is the portion of the DNA starting from the cap site and extending to the base just before the AUG translation initiation codon of the main coding sequence.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] This region may have sequences, such as the ribosome binding site and Kozak sequence, which determine the translation efficiency of the mRNA, or which may affect the stability of the mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 3′-end (three prime end) of a strand is so named due to it terminating at the hydroxyl group of the third carbon in the sugar-ring, and is known as the *tail end*.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 3′-hydroxyl is necessary in the synthesis of new nucleic acid molecules as it is ligated (joined) to the 5′-phosphate of a separate nucleotide, allowing the formation of strands of linked nucleotides.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] Molecular biologists can use nucleotides that lack a 3′-hydroxyl (dideoxyribonucleotides) to interrupt the replication of DNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] This technique is known as the dideoxy chain-termination method or the Sanger method, and is used to determine the order of nucleotides in DNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 3′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site of post-transcriptional polyadenylation, which attaches a chain of 50 to 250 adenosine residues to produce mature messenger RNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] This chain helps in determining how long the messenger RNA lasts in the cell, influencing how much protein is produced from it.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 3′-*flanking* region is a region of DNA that is not copied into the mature mRNA, but which is present adjacent to 3′-end of the gene.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] It was originally thought that the 3′-flanking DNA was not transcribed at all, but it was discovered to be transcribed into RNA and quickly removed during processing of the primary transcript to form the mature mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 3′-flanking region often contains sequences that affect the formation of the 3′-end of the message.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] It may also contain enhancers or other sites to which proteins may bind.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 3′-*untranslated* region (3′-UTR) is a region of the DNA which *is* transcribed into mRNA and becomes the 3′-end of the message, but which does not contain protein coding sequence.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] Everything between the stop codon and the polyA tail is considered to be 3′-untranslated.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] The 3′-untranslated region may affect the translation efficiency of the mRNA or the stability of the mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/3-end] It also has sequences which are required for the addition of the poly(A) tail to the message, including the hexanucleotide AAUAAA.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s10] Ribosomes, the organelles that catalyze protein synthesis, consist of a small 40S subunit and a large 60S subunit.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s10] Together these subunits are composed of 4 RNA species and approximately 80 structurally distinct proteins.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s10] This gene encodes a ribosomal protein that is a component of the 40S subunit.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s10] The protein belongs to the S10E family of ribosomal proteins.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s10] As is typical for genes encoding ribosomal proteins, there are multiple processed pseudogenes of this gene dispersed through the genome.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s10] Variable expression of this gene in colorectal cancers compared to adjacent normal tissues has been observed, although no correlation between the level of expression and the severity of the disease has been found.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s10] Mutations in the *RPS10* gene can cause Diamond–Blackfan anemia, a congenital anemia sometimes associated with bone marrow failure.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s10] RPS10 has been shown to interact with PTTG1.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s11] The protein belongs to the S17P family of ribosomal proteins.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s11] The gene product of the E. coli ortholog (ribosomal protein S17) is thought to be involved in the recognition of termination codons.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s11] This gene is co-transcribed with a small nucleolar RNA gene, which is located in its third intron.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s12] The protein belongs to the S12E family of ribosomal proteins.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s12] Increased expression of this gene in colorectal cancers compared to matched normal colonic mucosa has been observed.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s13] The protein belongs to the S15P family of ribosomal proteins.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s13] The protein has been shown to bind to the 5.8S rRNA in rat.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s13] The gene product of the *E. coli* ortholog (ribosomal protein S15) functions at early steps in ribosome assembly.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s13] This gene is co-transcribed with two U14 small nucleolar RNA genes, which are located in its third and fifth introns.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s13] RPS13 has been shown to interact with PDCD4.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s14] The protein belongs to the S11P family of ribosomal proteins.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s14] Transcript variants utilizing alternative transcription initiation sites have been described in the literature.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s14] In Chinese hamster ovary cells, mutations in this gene can lead to resistance to emetine, a protein synthesis inhibitor.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s15] The protein belongs to the S19P family of ribosomal proteins.
[src:translation-biology/40s-ribosomal-protein-s15] This gene has been found to be activated in various tumors, such as insulinomas, esophageal cancers, and colon cancers.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In translation, messenger RNA (mRNA) is decoded in a ribosome, outside the nucleus, to produce a specific amino acid chain, or polypeptide.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The polypeptide later folds into an active protein and performs its functions in the cell.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The polypeptide can also start folding during protein synthesis.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome facilitates decoding by inducing the binding of complementary transfer RNA (tRNA) anticodon sequences to mRNA codons.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The tRNAs carry specific amino acids that are chained together into a polypeptide as the mRNA passes through and is "read" by the ribosome.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The three stages of translation are initiation, elongation, and termination.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The basic process of protein production is the addition of one amino acid at a time to the end of a forming polypeptide chain.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This operation is performed by a ribosome.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] A ribosome is made up of two subunits, in the eukaryote a small (40S) subunit, and a large (60S) subunit.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] These subunits come together before the translation of mRNA into a protein to provide a location for translation to be carried out and a polypeptide to be produced.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The choice of amino acid type to add is determined by a messenger RNA (mRNA) molecule.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Each amino acid added is matched to a three-nucleotide subsequence of the mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] For each such triplet possible, the corresponding amino acid is accepted.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The successive amino acids added to the chain are matched to successive nucleotide triplets in the mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In this way, the sequence of nucleotides in the template mRNA chain determines the sequence of amino acids in the generated amino acid chain.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The addition of an amino acid occurs at the C-terminus of the peptide; thus, translation is said to be amine-to-carboxyl directed.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The mRNA carries genetic information encoded as a ribonucleotide sequence from the chromosomes to the ribosomes.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The ribonucleotides are "read" by translational machinery in a sequence of nucleotide triplets called codons.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Each of those triplets codes for a specific amino acid.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome molecules translate this code to a specific sequence of amino acids.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome is a multisubunit structure containing ribosomal RNA (rRNA) and proteins.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] It is the "factory" where amino acids are assembled into proteins.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Transfer RNAs (tRNAs) are small noncoding RNA chains (74–93 nucleotides) that transport amino acids to the ribosome.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The repertoire of tRNA genes varies widely between species, with some bacteria having between 20 and 30 genes while complex eukaryotes could have thousands. tRNAs have a site for amino acid attachment, and a site called an anticodon.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The anticodon is an RNA triplet complementary to the mRNA triplet that codes for their cargo amino acid.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Aminoacyl tRNA synthetases (enzymes) catalyze the bonding between specific tRNAs and the amino acids that their anticodon sequences call for.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The product of this reaction is an aminoacyl-tRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The amino acid is joined by its carboxyl group to the 3' OH of the tRNA by an ester bond.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] When the tRNA has an amino acid linked to it, the tRNA is termed "charged".
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases that mispair tRNAs with the wrong amino acids can produce mischarged aminoacyl-tRNAs, which can result in inappropriate amino acids at the respective position in the protein.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This "mistranslation" of the genetic code naturally occurs at low levels in most organisms, but certain cellular environments cause an increase in permissive mRNA decoding, sometimes to the benefit of the cell.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome has two binding sites for tRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] They are the aminoacyl site (abbreviated A), and the peptidyl site/ exit site (abbreviated P/E).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Concerning the mRNA, the three sites are oriented 5' to 3' E-P-A, because ribosomes move toward the 3' end of mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The A-site binds the incoming tRNA with the complementary codon on the mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The P/E-site holds the tRNA with the growing polypeptide chain.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] When an aminoacyl-tRNA initially binds to its corresponding codon on the mRNA, it is in the A site.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Then, a peptide bond forms between the amino acid of the tRNA in the A site and the amino acid of the charged tRNA in the P/E site.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The growing polypeptide chain is transferred to the tRNA in the A site.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Translocation occurs, moving the tRNA to the P/E site, now without an amino acid; the tRNA that was in the A site, now charged with the polypeptide chain, is moved to the P/E site and the uncharged tRNA leaves, and another aminoacyl-tRNA enters the A site to repeat the process.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] After the new amino acid is added to the chain, and after the tRNA is released out of the ribosome and into the cytosol, the energy provided by the hydrolysis of a GTP bound to the translocase EEF2 moves the ribosome down one codon towards the 3' end.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The energy required for translation of proteins is significant.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] For a protein containing *n* amino acids, the number of high-energy phosphate bonds required to translate it is 4*n*-1.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The rate of translation varies; it is significantly higher in prokaryotic cells (up to 17–21 amino acid residues per second) than in eukaryotic cells (up to 6–9 amino acid residues per second).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Translation proceeds in four phases: initiation, elongation, termination, and recycling.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Initiation involves the small subunit of the ribosome binding to the 5' end of mRNA with the help of initiation factors.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome and its associated factors assemble and bind to an mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The first tRNA is attached at the start codon.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This process is defined as either cap-dependent, in which the ribosome binds initially at the 5' cap and then travels to the stop codon, or as cap-independent, where the ribosome does not initially bind the 5' cap.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The 5' cap is added when the nascent pre-mRNA is about 20 nucleotides long.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Initiation of translation usually involves the interaction of certain key proteins, the initiation factors, with a special tag bound to the 5'-end of an mRNA molecule, the 5' cap, as well as with the 5' UTR.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] These proteins bind the small (40S) ribosomal subunit and hold the mRNA in place.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Binding of the cap by eIF4E is often considered the rate-limiting step of cap-dependent initiation, and the concentration of eIF4E is a regulatory nexus of translational control.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Recent structural biology results also indicated that a second eIF4A protein can simultaneously associate with the initiation complex, specifically interacting with eIF3.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The poly(A)-binding protein (PABP) also associates with the eIF4F complex via eIF4G, and binds the poly-A tail of most eukaryotic mRNA molecules.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This protein has been implicated in playing a role in circularization of the mRNA during translation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This 43S preinitiation complex (43S PIC) accompanied by the protein factors moves along the mRNA chain toward its 3'-end, in a process known as 'scanning', to reach the start codon (typically AUG).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In eukaryotes and archaea, the amino acid encoded by the start codon is methionine.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The Met-charged initiator tRNA (Met-tRNAiMet) is brought to the P-site of the small ribosomal subunit by eukaryotic initiation factor 2 (eIF2).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] It hydrolyzes GTP, and signals for the dissociation of several factors from the small ribosomal subunit, eventually leading to the association of the large subunit (or the 60S subunit).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The complete ribosome (80S) then commences translation elongation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Regulation of protein synthesis is partly influenced by phosphorylation of eIF2 (via the α subunit), which is a part of the eIF2-GTP-Met-tRNAiMet ternary complex (eIF2-TC).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] When large numbers of eIF2 are phosphorylated, protein synthesis is inhibited.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This occurs under amino acid starvation or after viral infection.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] However, a small fraction of this initiation factor is naturally phosphorylated.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Another regulator is 4EBP, which binds to the initiation factor eIF4E and inhibits its interactions with eIF4G, thus preventing cap-dependent initiation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] To oppose the effects of 4EBP, growth factors phosphorylate 4EBP, reducing its affinity for eIF4E and permitting protein synthesis.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] While protein synthesis is globally regulated by modulating the expression of key initiation factors as well as the number of ribosomes, individual mRNAs can have different translation rates due to the presence of regulatory sequence elements.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This has been shown to be important in a variety of settings including yeast meiosis and ethylene response in plants.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In addition, recent work in yeast and humans suggest that evolutionary divergence in cis-regulatory sequences can impact translation regulation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Additionally, RNA helicases such as DHX29 and Ded1/DDX3 participate in the process of translation initiation, especially for mRNAs with structured 5'UTRs.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The best-studied example of cap-independent translation initiation in eukaryotes uses the internal ribosome entry site (IRES).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Unlike cap-dependent translation, cap-independent translation does not require a 5' cap to initiate scanning from the 5' end of the mRNA until the start codon.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome can localize to the start site by direct binding, initiation factors, and/or ITAFs (IRES trans-acting factors) bypassing the need to scan the entire 5' UTR.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This method of translation is important in conditions that require the translation of specific mRNAs during cellular stress, when overall translation is reduced.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Examples include factors responding to apoptosis and stress-induced responses.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Elongation depends on elongation factors.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] At the end of the initiation step, the mRNA is positioned so that the next codon can be translated during the elongation stage of protein synthesis.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The initiator tRNA occupies the P site in the ribosome, and the A site is ready to receive an aminoacyl-tRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] During chain elongation, each additional amino acid is added to the nascent polypeptide chain in a three-step microcycle.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The steps in this microcycle are (1) positioning the correct aminoacyl-tRNA in the A site of the ribosome, which is brought into that site by eEF1, (2) forming the peptide bond, and (3) shifting the mRNA by one codon relative to the ribosome with the help of eEF2.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Eukaryotic mRNA precursors must be processed in the nucleus (e.g., capping, polyadenylation, splicing) in ribosomes before they are exported to the cytoplasm for translation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Translation can also be affected by ribosomal pausing, which can trigger endonucleolytic attack of the tRNA, a process termed mRNA no-go decay.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Ribosomal pausing also aids co-translational folding of the nascent polypeptide on the ribosome, and delays protein translation while it is encoding tRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This can trigger ribosomal frameshifting.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The last tRNA validated by the small ribosomal subunit (***accommodation***) transfers the amino acid.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] It carries to the large ribosomal subunit which binds it to one of the preceding admitted tRNA (***transpeptidation***).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome then moves to the next mRNA codon to continue the process (***translocation***), creating an amino acid chain.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In bacterial translation, and archaeal translation, translation occurs in the cytosol, where the ribosome binds to the mRNA.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In eukaryotes, translation can occur in the cytoplasm and also across the membrane of the endoplasmic reticulum through a process called co-translational translocation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Many types of transcribed RNA, such as tRNA, ribosomal RNA, and small nuclear RNA, do not undergo a translation into proteins.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Several antibiotics act by inhibiting translation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] These include anisomycin, cycloheximide, chloramphenicol, tetracycline, streptomycin, erythromycin, and puromycin.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Prokaryotic ribosomes have a different structure from that of eukaryotic ribosomes, and thus antibiotics can specifically target bacterial infections without harming a eukaryotic host's cells.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Termination of elongation depends on the release factor eRF1 that recognizes all three stop codons.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] When a stop codon is reached, termination of the polypeptide occurs the ribosome is disassembled and the completed polypeptide is released. eRF3 is a ribosome-dependent GTPase that helps eRF1 release the completed polypeptide.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The human genome encodes a few genes whose mRNA stop codons are surprisingly leaky: In these genes, termination of translation is inefficient due to special RNA bases in the vicinity of the stop codon.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Leaky termination in these genes leads to translational readthrough of up to 10% of the stop codons of these genes.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Some of these genes encode functional protein domains in their readthrough extension so that new protein isoforms can arise.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This process has been termed 'functional translational readthrough'.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] When the A site of the ribosome is occupied by a stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA) on the mRNA, creating the primary structure of a protein. tRNA usually cannot recognize or bind to stop codons.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Instead, the stop codon induces the binding of a release factor protein (RF1 & RF2) that prompts the disassembly of the entire ribosome/mRNA complex by the hydrolysis of the polypeptide chain from the peptidyl transferase center of the ribosome.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Drugs or special sequence motifs on the mRNA can change the ribosomal structure so that near-cognate tRNAs are bound to the stop codon instead of the release factors.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In such cases of 'translational readthrough', translation continues until the ribosome encounters the next stop codon.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] When the synthesised protein is released the complex ribosome disassembles into its subunits for recycling.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The rate of error in synthesizing proteins has been estimated to be between 1 in 105 and 1 in 103 misincorporated amino acids, depending on the experimental conditions.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The rate of premature translation abandonment, instead, has been estimated to be of the order of magnitude of 10−4 events per translated codon.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Translation is one of the key energy consumers in cells, hence it is strictly regulated.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Numerous mechanisms have evolved that control and regulate translation in eukaryotes as well as prokaryotes.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Regulation of translation can impact the global rate of protein synthesis which is closely coupled to the metabolic and proliferative state of a cell.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Other methods such as toeprinting assay can also be used to determine the location of ribosomes of a particular mRNA in vitro, and footprints of other proteins regulating translation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] To delve deeper into this intricate process, scientists typically use a technique known as ribosome profiling.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This method enables researchers to take a snapshot of the translatome, showing which parts of the mRNA are being translated into proteins by ribosomes at a given time.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Ribosome profiling provides valuable insights into translation dynamics, revealing the complex interplay between gene sequence, mRNA structure, and translation regulation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Expanding on this concept, single-cell ribosome profiling, is a technique that allows the study of the translation process at the resolution of individual cells.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Single-cell ribosome profiling has revealed that genetic differences and their subsequent expression as mRNAs can also impact translation rate in an RNA-specific manner.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Single-cell ribosome profiling has the potential to shed light on the heterogeneous nature of cells, leading to a more nuanced understanding of how translation regulation can impact cell behavior, metabolic state, and responsiveness to various stimuli or conditions.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Incorporating amino acids that deviate from the genetic code predictions is usually detected as amino acid substitutions in proteins and peptides.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Such alternate RNA decoding results in stable and abundant proteins in both mouse and human tissues.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The abundance of such substitutions is determined by multiple mechanisms, including codon frequency, codon–anticodon mismatches, RNA modifications, and protein stability.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In some cells certain amino acids can be depleted and thus affect translation efficiency.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] For instance, activated T cells secrete interferon-γ which triggers intracellular tryptophan shortage by upregulating the indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase 1 (IDO1) enzyme.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Despite tryptophan depletion, in-frame protein synthesis continues across tryptophan codons.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This is achieved by incorporation of phenylalanine instead of tryptophan.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The resulting peptides are called W>F "substitutants".
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Such W>F substitutants are abundant in certain cancer types and have been associated with increased IDO1 expression.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Functionally, W>F substitutants can impair protein activity.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Translational control is critical for the development and survival of cancer.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Cancer cells must frequently regulate the translation phase of gene expression, though it is not fully understood why translation is targeted over steps like transcription.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] While cancer cells often have genetically altered translation factors, it is much more common for cancer cells to modify the levels of existing translation factors.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Several major oncogenic signaling pathways, including the RAS–MAPK, PI3K/AKT/mTOR, MYC, and WNT–β-catenin pathways, ultimately reprogram the genome via translation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Cancer cells also control translation to adapt to cellular stress.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] During stress, the cell translates mRNAs that can mitigate the stress and promote survival.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] An example of this is the expression of AMPK in various cancers; its activation triggers a cascade that can ultimately allow the cancer to escape apoptosis (programmed cell death) triggered by nutrition deprivation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Future cancer therapies may involve disrupting the translation machinery of the cell to counter the downstream effects of cancer.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The process of amino acid building to create protein in translation is a subject of various physic models for a long time starting from the first detailed kinetic models such as or others taking into account stochastic aspects of translation and using computer simulations.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Many chemical kinetics-based models of protein synthesis have been developed and analyzed in the last four decades.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Beyond chemical kinetics, various modeling formalisms such as Totally Asymmetric Simple Exclusion Process, Probabilistic Boolean Networks, Petri Nets and max-plus algebra have been applied to model the detailed kinetics of protein synthesis or some of its stages.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] A basic model of protein synthesis that takes into account all eight 'elementary' processes has been developed, following the paradigm that "useful models are simple and extendable".
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The simplest model *M0* is represented by the reaction kinetic mechanism (Figure M0).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] It was generalised to include 40S, 60S and initiation factors (IF) binding (Figure M1').
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] It was extended further to include effect of microRNA on protein synthesis.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Most of models in this hierarchy can be solved analytically.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] These solutions were used to extract 'kinetic signatures' of different specific mechanisms of synthesis regulation.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] It is also possible to translate either by hand (for short sequences) or by computer (after first programming one appropriately, see section below); this allows biologists and chemists to draw out the primary amino acid sequence of the encoded protein on paper.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] First, convert each template DNA base to its RNA complement (note that the complement of A is now U), as shown below.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Note that the template strand of the DNA is the one the RNA is polymerized against; the other DNA strand would be the same as the RNA, but with thymine instead of uracil.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Then split the RNA into triplets (groups of three bases).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Note that there are 3 translation "windows", or reading frames, depending on where you start reading the code.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Finally, use the table at Genetic code to translate the above into a structural formula as used in chemistry.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] This will give the primary structure of the protein.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] However, proteins tend to fold, depending in part on hydrophilic and hydrophobic segments along the chain.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Secondary structure can often still be guessed, but the proper tertiary structure is often very hard to determine.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] In order to determine the precise 3D structure and atomic interactions, Structural biology and several other Biophysics methods are used.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Whereas other aspects such as the 3D structure, called tertiary structure, of protein can only be predicted using sophisticated algorithms, the amino acid sequence, called primary structure, can be determined solely from the nucleic acid sequence with the aid of a translation table.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] There are many computer programs capable of translating a DNA/RNA sequence into a protein sequence.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Normally this is performed using the Standard Genetic Code, however, few programs can handle all the "special" cases, such as the use of the alternative initiation codons which are biologically significant.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] For instance, the rare alternative start codon CTG codes for Methionine when used as a start codon, and for Leucine in all other positions.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Example: Condensed translation table for the Standard Genetic Code (from the NCBI Taxonomy webpage).
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] The "Starts" row indicate three start codons, UUG, CUG, and the very common AUG.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] It also indicates the first amino acid residue when interpreted as a start: in this case it is all methionine.
[src:translation-biology/translation-biology] Even when working with ordinary eukaryotic sequences such as the Yeast genome, it is often desired to be able to use alternative translation tables—namely for translation of the mitochondrial genes.
